    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>HATE-CRIME LAW</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By KAREN DeMASTERS</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Demasters, Karen</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>US Supreme Court rules that New Jersey's 1981 law allowing judges to extend penalties for hate crimes is unconstitutional; holds jury, not judge, has to determine whether crime is hate-related (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>New Jersey's 1981 law allowing judges to extend penalties for crimes committed because of a defendant's prejudices is unconstitutional, the United States Supreme Court ruled last week. The court ruled that a jury, not a judge, has to determine whether a crime was hate-related. The ruling was issued in a case involving a Vineland man, Charles Apprendi, who shot at the home of the only black family in his neighborhood.</p>
        <p>KAREN DeMASTERS</p>
      </block>
